recent article in this very publication goes far to explaining the rise of home education in the UK; &#10;About one in five of all children ? 19% ? fail to achieve level 2 in writing, while 16% miss this target in reading. &#10;This is not statistical noise.&#10;This is a failure of state schools that have been entrusted to teach children.&#10;But beyond that, it is a failure of the the parents themselves as they are the ones under the 1996 Education Act who are responsible for ensuring an education of their children. &#10;Families that lawfully elect to home educate have a difficult time &quot;listening to&quot; and taking guidance from organizations that are failing one out of five children. &#10;I know many families that are basic hard working middle class families who want the best for their children but are unable to fund a private education or move into a better catchment area. &#10;Home Education is simply a reaction to what the state has failed to do.&#10;If the state continues to fail, home education will grow.&#10;If the state produces better and better educational results, home education will decline."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1382" language="en" documentId="1007" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="MidlandsStewart" date="07 November 2009 11:25am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6753428" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="4" thumbsDown="0" origId="1007" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="170"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="171" end="296"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="297" end="400"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="401" end="518"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="519" end="549"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="550" end="628"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="629" end